SDF.AX 12m Price Target: A\(6.70 Price: A\)6.14 Upside: 9.1%

Overall Result: a) SDF's FY26 Guidance for Underlying NPATA slightly softer: Midpoint of guidance is A\$370m v VA consensus of A\$375m. 2) FY25 Underlying NPATA result in line: with GS/Consensus at A\$192m. 3) 2H25 Dividend in line: Dividend of 11.7cps vs GSe of 12.0cps.

Key takeaways from SDF's FY25 result: 1) SDF Broking margins expanded with organic growth broadly stable on pcp: 2H25 Broking margin expanded by \(\sim 45\) bps to \(40.5\%\) v pcp and organic growth was broadly stable v pcp at \(7.4\%\) over 2H25 - rate increases moderating with focus on subsidiary performance improvement. 2) SDF Agency margins / organic growth moderated: 2H25 Organic growth of \(4.8\%\) v pcp of \(11.4\%\) and Margins contracted by \(\sim 90\) bps to \(49\%\) ; driven by investment in underwriting and claims systems. 3) Group margins expanded: by \(1\%\) to \(34.8\%\) v pcp. 4) SDF flagged capacity to borrow A\$365m and remain within maximum gearing ratio of \(35\%\) : Gearing was \(27.0\%\) as at Jun- 25.

Outlook: a) No FY26 Trapped capital guidance: FY25 acquisitions were completed in line with guidance \(\sim\) A\$300m. FY26 acquisitive growth of \(3\%\) reflects FY25/FY26 acquisitions. b) Organic growth of \(3 - 7\%\) in FY26: Driven by \(3 - 5\%\) rate increases, operating leverage and cost out initiatives.

Other items: a) Acquisition of Novum Underwriting Partners: Specialty and wholesale broker in the US providing digital delivery of insurance programs (marketplace, quoting, servicing renewals). b) Chair succession: Mr. Frank O'Halloran AM retiring as Chair of the Board on 31 October 2025 and will be succeeded by Ms. Vicki Allen.
V are Buy rated SDF with 12- m PT of A\(6.70 unchanged.
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Research estimates. See disclosures for details.

Overall result summary: The FY25 result was in line with guidance provided by SDF to the market. All key guidance notes were also at the midpoint of SDF's FY25 guidance range as expected by GS and consensus. 2) FY26 guidance - EBITA above GS and consensus, underlying NPATA slightly below: For FY26, midpoint of EBITA guidance is A\(657.5m (GSe - A\) 653m, VA consensus A\)642m), Underlying NPAT of A\)320m (GSe at A\)326m, VA consensus A\)321m), diluted EPS growth of 8% on FY25 (GSe at \~10%) and underlying NPATA of A\)370m (GSe at A\)380m, VA consensus A\)375m). Guidance assumes 3- 5% premium rate increases. See Exhibit 8 for SDF's FY25 guidance bridge.

Key numbers from the result: 1) Underlying 2H25 EBITA in line at A\)329m vs GSe of A\)327m (VA consensus of A\)329m). 2) Underlying 2H25 NPAT in line at A\)167m vs GSe of A\)166m (VA consensus of A\)167m). 3) Underlying 2H25 NPATA in line at A\)192m vs GSe of A\)191m (VA consensus of A\)192m). 4) Dividend of 11.7cps vs GSe of 12.0cps.

SDF Broking organic growth stable over 2H25 v pcp: 2H25 underlying EBITA of A\(244.1m grew by 8% over 2H25 on pcp, split 7.4% organic (2H24 was 7.5%) and 0.8% acquisition led (2H24 was 8.6%) (refer to Exhibit 3). Organic growth was driven by moderate price rises and subsidiary performance improvement initiatives roll out. SDF also flagged additional growth of 3.5% from increasing equity stakes in brokers resulting in a reduction in NCI. Equity ownership now at 81% vs 77% in FY24.

SDF Agencies organic growth slowing over 2H25 v pcp: 2H25 Underlying EBITA of A\(115.3m grew 5% on pcp, driven predominantly by organic growth supported by price and volume (refer to Exhibit 5). FY26 and equity ownership remained unchanged at 89%. SDF flagged that CPS230 and Lloyd's Operational Resilience regulatory requirements had been implemented across the portfolios and additional investment spend had been made to update underwriting and claims systems.

SDF International: ISU Steadfast exceeded budgeted FY25 profit again and now has US\(7.9bn in GWP. H.W. Wood acquired in December 2024, rebranded to HWS Specialty. Strategic acquisition of majority stake in Novum taken in August 2025 which provides opportunity to expand market capabilities internationally and in Australia.

Group EBIT margin expanded over 2H25 v pcp: 2H25 EBITA margin was 34.8%, an improvement of 100bps vs pcp reflecting greater leverage of central resources across the Group. SDF Broking 2H25 EBITA margin expanded 45bps v pcp. SDF Agencies margin reduced 90bps over 2H25 v pvp: due to additional spend to update underwriting and claims systems (see Exhibit 2).
SDF flagged capacity to borrow A\(365m and remain within maximum gearing ratio of 35%: Gearing was 27.0% as at Jun- 25.

M&A activity and pipeline - FY25 in line with guidance; no FY26 guidance provided: SDF completed acquisitions per guidance \~A\)300m of acquisitions over FY25, as targeted. No guidance on FY26 acquisitions has been provided. M&A
**pipeline:** \(\sim \mathrm {A}\Phi 441\mathrm {m}\) of EBITA can be acquired across SDF's network (see Exhibit 7).

· **Chair succession and appointment of new NED:** Mr. Frank O'Halloran AM will retire as Chair of the Board on 31 October 2025 at the conclusion of the upcoming 2025 AGM and will be succeeded by Ms. Vicki Allen. Mr. Michael Goodwin will join the Board effective 15 September 2025.
· **SCTP continues to grow:** FY25 GWP transaction A$1,400m, up 15.6% on pcp.

· **Operating environment: a)** SDF expects continued price increases of ~3-5% in guidance, with mid-market still experiencing rate increases but rates in selected lines including cyber and PI moderating.

SDF is a group of insurance brokers providing largely commercial insurance solutions for SME clients. SDF also operates the SDF network of brokers. We are Buy rated on the stock. We like SDF because of the industry structure favouring insurance brokers. 1) Premium rate environment supportive of organic growth trends (albeit moderating); 2) Little to no exposure to underwriting risk with revenues largely dependent on premiums written; 3) An opportunity to acquire EPS accretively with unlisted acquisitions at multiples accretive to earnings (including offshore); 4) A
defensive business model which is relatively resilient to economic activity; 5) Valuation appeal compared to global peers.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FC and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
